This note, for the moment is the user guide for my [[applib]]

-----

The [[commonlib]] satisfies the question:  beyond the functions in a function library, where are the other functions to make a stand-alone application.

!!! installation:

See [[applemcg, commonlib |https://github.com/applemcg/commonlib]]on my github account

-----
The compromise I've made here is not to put all the functions in a single source-able file, but rather in two files:

* the function lib -- functions providing the public interface, the user commands, the entry points, and
* a [[commonlib]]

I've moved the handful of function libraries into a single directory, suitable of, say ''git'' maintenance.  Here's the current inventory:

* applib -- functions to find user tree of all used functions
* commonlib -- the library of widely used functions
* ftplib -- first application, command-line ftp
* refreshlib --a special-purpose application:  write an HTML file which REFRESHs the link to another page. sort of a user-managed link-shortener.

to which, before I'm ready to release the package, I'll likely include backuplib.

!!! history

my shell functions practice is now over two decades old.  an early edition was a functoin library i called hennies -- "you've got to be a one-liner to get in here".  not every function fit easily as a one-liner. By the turn of the century I'd compromised that ideal.  

the first half of the aughts, i taught algebra and geometry, then ran the computer lab at Benedictine Academy, Elizabeth NJ, so little shell practice.  In '06, I was pulled back into technology, training application languages: Tcl and Java, at Fidessa in Manhattan.  While 
''csh'' was their official, or business shell, the  support desks were free to use ksh, bash.  

I was shortly re-united with the better shells, where I've remained for the last dozen years. 

Before getting ahead, i note my //discovery// of Unix and the shell command on January 15th, 1979 in Palo Alto, CA, at Ford Aerospace Western Development Lab.  I'd been sent  there from FACC's Colorado Springs office by our Configuration Manager, Mike McCormick, as the first COS person to become acquainted with V7/PWB Unix.  Our plan was to run V7 Unix on PDP 11/70s  to develop an Air Force communicators project for the NATO forces. But that's another story.

This current vision of Shell Functional development may be replaced by yet another , but my sense is it will be but a tweak.  This commonlib practice is based on the last dozen years, with insights from both shell usage, but also software principals, the most recent is to understand [[WhatIsDry]].

Also, I'm looking for a 2nd Edition of my book, [[Shell Functions|http://leanpub.com/shellfunctions]].   For the last two plus years, I've been experimenting with what I've called the [[SHELF Standard|https://github.com/applemcg/shelf]]. 

The [[commonlib]] practice recognizes functions developed in the SHELF Standard.  However, instead of developing to a standard, I'm building a practice based on lessons learned from the standard.  I prefer synthesis over analysis.  Building from the bottom up.

Now, go to the [[Commonlib Development]]







!! to the Moment

The four-mentioned libraries (applib, commonlib, ftplib, and refreshlib) are the basis of the new practice.  Two, the ''ftplib'' and ''refreshlib'' are special-purpose,and in developing them, I discovered the practice.

When I recognized a number of common functions in both libraries, many pulled from work on the SHELF, I decided to compromise.  The need to keep identical functions up-to-date in two or more libraries told me to bite the bullet and have a single shared library, on which any other might be built.

So I pulled common functions from ftp_app and refresh_app in to commonlib.   And, a function  i've had  in the stable for a few years called ''app_fun'' which recursively cycles through the call graph of a function or functions until all used functions are identified.   Here's a sample of the practice, It's being used to produce the third application library: ''applib''

```
$ app_fun $(functions ftplib commonlib | 
      sort | tee .ftp.lib) | 
      sort | tee .ftp.app
```

The list in //.ftp.lib// is the unique functions defined in the two libraries,  The list in //.ftp.app//
includes those as well as all the functions from the call graph.   Then application of a most under-used command produces the lists to place which function belongs where.

```
$ comm -23 .ftp.{app,lib}             # list functions in neither lib
$ declare -f $(!!) | tee -a commonlib # writes functions in neither lib into the commonlib 
```

Re-running the prior command, app_fun should produce identical lists.  

A quick inspection of this history shows little new.   The last example shows only commands: ''comm, declare'' and ''tee''.   Therefore all the discovery takes place in ''app_fun'' and ''functions'' .  The functions function has been around for quite some time.   It's current spec:

> //from the standard input or named files, return the first occurrence of the name of defined functions//

In order to make function names readily discovered, the function expects a function to have been displayed by the ''declare -f'' command.

The app_fun function and following code fragment have been realized in the ''app_needs'' function.









Colm Toibin quotes Conor Cruise O'Brien about the "twilight time after the fall of Parnell and before the 1916 Rebellion":

> There is for all of us a twilight zone of time, stretching back for a generation or two before we were born, which never quite belongs to the rest of history.  Our elders have talked their memories into our memories until we come to possess some sense of a continuity exceeding and traversing our own individual being ... Children of small and vocal communities are likely to possess it to a high degree and, if they are imaginative, have the power of incorporating into their own lives a significant span of time before their individual births.  

From this, I take away two thoughts:  

* the "chicken or egg" question --   since much of O'Brien's writing is post '60s, where lies the origin of the "twilight zone" metaphor, his writing or Rod Serling and his 50' - 60s TV show?
* this supports my idea that history should be taught backwards.  Since "current events" are stories from the student's life-times, mostly right now, then history is everything which preceded.   The hope of reversing the course of history instruction would expand the "power of incorporating into their own lives" to a wider community.












Here's a little program to unpack CSV files into TSV.   I prefer a TSV format, since the TAB is the field delimiter of choice in [[/RDB|https://compbio.soe.ucsc.edu/rdb/]].  As Rob Manis said, 

> the only field delimiter is the TAB character; it's the one character you won't find in a data field.

!! requirements

So, this little program does two things:

* It eliminates spaces in the first record, assumed to contain the field names, which preferably don't need spaces in their name, and
* it converts delimiting commas into tabs, assuming that routine commas are enclosed in a quoted field.

Turning the resulting file into an /RDB file is handled at the command-line, or function level.

!! usage
To convert the result into a proper /RDB table, the first record needs a proper header record:

* the first line of the /RDB table is the tab-separated field names
* the second line of the /RDB table is composed of dash-fields, preferably equal-length to their field names

```
csv_2rdb () 
{ 
    : produce TSV, RDB, TXT from file.CSV;
    : date: 2018-05-30;
    set ${1%.???}.{csv,tsv,rdb,txt};
    fmdos $1 | csvwhdr > $2;
    ( rdb_hdr $(sed 1q $2);
    tail +2 $2 ) | tee $3 | justify > $4
}
```
The function accepts a CSV file, converts to TSV, uses that first record to write an /RDB header, and the remaining records of the TSV, which taken together form a proper /RDB file, which is finally converted into a printable column-aligned TXT file.  

!! code

Here is the C program which is compiled and loaded:

> $ set csvwhdr; cc -o $1 $1.c

And the code, separated for clarity:  [[csvwhdr.c]]








```
/*
 * ------------- converts CSV to TSV, assumes single HDR record	--
 *
 * csvwhdr.c	2018-05-30
 * csv2tsv.c	2017-09-20
 * crypt.c	2014-03-04
 * Main		2012-06-25
 */

#include <stdio.h>
#include <ctype.h>

#define toggle(x) x = 1-x /* off => ON or ON => off */

int main (int argc, char *argv[])
{	
  int nr = 0;             /* think AWK */
  int c;
  int quoting = 0  ;      /* are we collecting a quoted field
                           * or splitting fields
                           */

  while ( (c = getchar()) != EOF )
    {
      if ( !quoting && c == ',' )
	{
	  putchar ( '\t' );
	}
      else if ( c == '\n' )
	{
	  putchar ( '\n' );	  
	  nr++;
	}	  
      else if (nr == 0 && !isalnum(c))
	{
	  continue;       /* only alphaNumeric in HDR record */
	}
      else if ( c == '"' )
	{
	  toggle( quoting );
	}
      else
	{
	  putchar ( c );
	}
    }
}
```






coffee drink time impact,   Paul Pedant, who hangs out at the IT Toolbox, assesses the value of any work on a programming feature in units of cups of coffee.

{{April 2020}}








[[CYO Camp, Summer of 59]]

I'm glad [[he remembers|http://mcgowans.org/pubs/family/Dadstory/Becoming_a_Catholic.html]] the [[Boundary Waters|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boundary_Waters_Canoe_Area_Wilderness]] adventure.
<hr>

I'm sure it's one that mom/Grandma would like to forget.  In which we paddled for a week with Steve and Nancy Anderson, friends from our work, back in the day.  The long paddle home may have cost us a friendship.  This trip to the BWCA was around the 4th of July '71, just to put a date on it.
<hr>

The part he may have forgotten was the summer of '59, probably a year or two after the missed trip.  My good buddy of the time, Dave "Bosie" Briscoe (who also may have had to skip the Scout trip), and I went to a CYO camp in "Lake of the Woods".   Dad drove us up, Dave's dad picked us up after a two week stay in the camp. At the time, it was the northern most point of the USA.   Alaska became a state on that particular 4th.  Our camp, on Oak Island, was within a mile across the water from the [[Northwest Angle |https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northwest_Angle]], a piece of MN, otherwise unconnected by land with the rest of the US.   Enna-who (paraphrase MJ Jr), on the evening of that 4th, the few residents of the Angle Inlet had an OK fireworks display, their last hurrah as the US of A's northern most point of land.    I don't remember the total, but id think there were less than 200 total at the CYO camp; we felt priviledged to be the few who witnessed that event in American history.


Oh yes, and another part of the story:  the reason Dad permitted that trip was the camp was served by a chaplain, who conducted a mass on Sunday, the change-over day for those who were only there for a week.  And for those of you still with me, we did _not_ paddle the breadth of the Lake of the Woods to reach the camp; i'd say it was at least an hour boat-ride out of [[Warroad, MN|https://www.warroadmn.org/]], the parental exchange location _and_ the home of Hockey Olympians of '60s and '80s fame.

Here' a [[contemporary map, showing Oak Island|http://oakislandresort.com/mapangleinletbignarrowsyoungsbay.htm]] in relation to the Northwest Angle.  I'm thinking the CYO camp has been given over to commercial interests.






[[Daily Reading]]

If you have'' bash'' with a suitable ''date ''utility, with a browser accepting an ''open'' command, then these work out of the box on your command line.

The  ''`: date:`'' stamps are tags indicating the date the function was saved in its library,

Note the ${*:-open} idiom.  It says use the open command with your browser to open an http connection.  

If you don't care to read or listen to today's reading, you can:

```
$ daily_reading echo
$ daily_audio echo
```
To show the links.  Then you could also 

$ open $(daily_reading echo)

to more fully appreciate what's happening.

[[daily_reading_code]]:
click on this link to see just the code:

{{daily_reading_code}}










```
daily_reading () 
{ 
    : the USCCB daily bible reading TEXT;
    : date: 2019-04-01;
    : date: 2020-01-06;
    : date: 2020-02-18;
    ${*:-open} http://usccb.org/bible/readings/$(date '+%m%d%y').cfm
}
daily_audio () 
{ 
    : the USCCB daily bible reading AUDIO;
    : date: 2019-04-01;
    : date: 2020-01-06;
    : date: 2020-02-18;
    ${*:-open} http://ccc.usccb.org/cccradio/NABPodcasts/$(date +%Y/%y_%m_%d).mp3
}
```






On ''Tuesday, Wednesday, 4/24 - 25,'' with a number of fraternity brothers, I attended the internment of Dave Thomas Dinan at Arlington Natl Cemetery.   As a marine pilot, Dave was shot down in Laos in March 1969.   His final remains were recovered last year,  and returned just this week.  From the MIT/PKT classes of '65 (Dave's): Peter Heineman, Dick Morgen, Larry Gajdos, Jack Coughlin, and '66: myself, Mike Dunlavey, Fran Capitanio.  Others in order: '59: Gene (Monk) Montrone, '61: Bill Rossi, Emil Signes, '62: Don Colosimo, and 64: [[Leo Cardillo|2019-07-29, Monday]], Jim Volkert.  This composite [img[DaveDinanComposite]] 

is thanks to Don Colosimo,  who was not able to attend.

We met Dave's brothers, Charlie and John, who really organized the whole event, charged up by Ed Sykes, in Dave's flight, and Mark Rockoff, MIT '69, from Linden NJ.

I hope to connect Ed, who's writing a book about Dave, with the fraternity brothers.  Ed had delivered the eulogy at the chapel service, introducing Dave's brothers: genetic, tactical wing, and MIA searchers.    Ed told me, he'd like to hear about Dave's relationship with our group of brothers.

Here is an [[eight minute video of his internment|http://bit.ly/dinanmemorial]]

And here's a link to a [[video from brother Charlie|https://vimeo.com/327516447]]

Today, i've built [[an app|http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3/commonplace/software/swdiary-2018.html#dd_code]]  to analyze results of running [[dedoop|https://github.com/edsu/dedoop]] (de - dup) on files in my HOME/Sites directory where I store [[my web pages|http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3]].

While the app isn't completely general, it's suitable to copy/paste into your own space and with a two or three changes, put it to work for yourself.  This page serves as both a [[manual page|manpp]] and user documentation, [[the code|http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3/commonplace/software/swdiary-2018.html#dd_code]] being at the first link above.

The dedoop tool is found at the second link above.   To download dedoop, you will need [[Python3|https://www.python.org/downloads/]] first.  Once that is installed, copy the dd_app code, and you may proceed here.

!!! NAME

dd_app -- dedoop application

!!! SYNOPSIS

```
$ source dd_app    # loads the app
$ dd_init          # shows example usage
$ dd_code          # the code listing
$ dd_run           # runs the analysis
$ dd_saved         # the saved data
```

!!! DESCRIPTION

The dd_app contains functions to:

* show example usage
* run the analysis
* point to the code
* point to this manual page
* display and/or use the dedoop results and user analysis files

The instructions to customize the short application are below

!!! FILES

* `HOME/ar/sites/data.json` -- results of the dedoop run
* `HOME/lib/dd_data.txt` -- primary output of dd_run, see discussion below
* `HOME/lib/dd_summary.txt` -- brief tabular summary of all files, duplicate or not.

The functions dd_ input, saved, and sumry are what i call SmartFunctions.   See the `dd_run` function for what that means.

!!! OUTPUT FORMATS

!!!! dd_data.txt
Fields:

# dedoop filename
# count of identical, dedooped files
# first file name -- often the preferred file
# second file name -- optional: one other instance of the same file contents, i.e a duplicate

!!!! dd_summary.txt
Fields: 

# population -- number of files with nLinks
# nLinks --  monotonic list of link counts
# uniques -- summed thru counts, last is total unique files
# dups -- summed thru counts, last is total duplicate files
# file count -- summed thru counts, last is total files in the population.

!!! CUSTOMIZE

To customize dd_app for your case, there are three functions to touch.  First the optional features offered by dedoop, and a preference on your part:

# the source tree for dedoop analysis
# the output directory for the dedoop files
# your preferred directory within the source tree (#1)

In the current code:

# Sites
# ar/sites
# Sites/mcgowans_org

The `dd_init` function is  the clue: these directories are all with respect to your HOME directory. ( `$ cd` )

So change these functions:

*dd_init -- optional since it's only a hint. but, to keep consistent with your usage, 
*dd_input -- update the output directory
*dd_favor -- update the preferred directory

Also, note the dd_saved and dd_sumry functions.   Make sure you have a HOME/lib directory.

!!! AUTHOR

MartyMcGowan

For the inner-circle, here's how to DecodeMySig, which is: 

 `=*+[]+  Marty McGowan `

```
=   Pat and I
*   our three kids
+   Chip and Laurie's two
[]  Maura and Mark's four
+   Katie and Justin's two
```

It's evolved over the years, e.g before '09, when my parents were alive, it started '==', no children was a '.', one a '-'.   If anyone should get to five, how about a 'V'?

So, i guess when the folks were alive, and before any grandkids, it might have looked like   =IX=*...

It's my plan to collect the memorial tributes being poured out for [[Dick Sparapany]] here:







> A friend replying to WhatIsDry, having annotated the underlying paper.

Hi, Marty,

Software creation, as an art form, is unlike other art where at the start, the artist has a vision of what the final creation might look like -- even if they change their mind along the path of creation.  Software creation is more like traversing a long maze: at its entrance, you understand that there is a final destination, but you cannot see its location, you can only see the upcoming decision you need to make, and as you travel, more of the maze is revealed to you.

Organizing code into generalized structures creates a kind of shape and somewhat informs or even dictates the directions forward that it can easily go.  Doing this too early, when not enough of the maze is yet revealed, may increase the cost of back-tracking and altering a past decision.  In the worst case, this is at odds with human nature's desire to avoid sunk cost, and can result in pursuing a sub-optimal path, or worse, one that will never yield a successful path through the maze to its final destination.

This is why I take great pain to mentor software developers into respecting and understanding DRY, but never applying it sooner than is absolutely clear what the correct way to reduce or remove repetition is.  It requires a great deal of humility to say "I think I know, but I really don't know with real certainty, what the final shape should look like" and to leave the duplication in place until you do.

The sign of an experienced software creator is that they allow themselves to violate DRY only as long as necessary and not a moment longer.  Those less experienced either apply it too soon, or wait too long or even never applying it at all, resulting in unnecessary baggage that will need to be maintained.

Thanks for asking,

-- 
Dossy Shiobara

Today, we learned of the overnight death of a great American, ''Congressman EE Cummings of Maryland''.  He was a personal hero of mine.   He was a champion of the individual, each of us, in particular those who had less.   His advocacy of making each minute count, and If we don't  say we stood up for democracy in 2019, what claim can we make for America's future and that of all our descendants.

He was rightfully called [["the keeper of the nation's conscience"|https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/elijah-cummings-was-the-keeper-of-the-nations-conscience/2019/10/17/211b6826-f121-11e9-8693-f487e46784aa_story.html]] and "gave hope to the hopeless"

Stories that flow from [[Email on April 1st]]:

Anecdote:  in the early days of email,  1985, while at the Unix Systems Lab in Summit, NJ,   because of AT&T's excellent user directory, it was possible to send email to everyone a building.  On that April 1st, I chose to send a letter to the roughly 300 people in the SF (Summit Facility)

   "Any official email sent today will have to be resent tomorrow".

To which the division secretary replied.

   "Who gave you the authority to send that email".

The group leader for the tools, incl mail

-----

Sending mail to all who worked in Piscatway for Al Stachiw's friend

-----

The day, in POST when I took down an entire Business Unit







> This note is clipped from a 3/23/16 email to my brother [[Mike|mailto:mike.mcgowan@pobox.com]], 17 years younger, who might not share similar computing experience.  Mike had introduced me to Evernote, where I'd first saved it. 

In 1984, (or by 1984) we were on Unix (System 3, V, ...) using 24 x 80 character terminals, HP 2600 series.   For much of the year: Jan - June, I was at [[INteractive Systems|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interactive_Systems_Corporation]] in Boston, where we were porting those flavors of Unix from AT&T to an IBM workstation, code-named AIWS (Advanced Integrated ~WorkStation), on a RISC (Reduced Instruction Set Computer), the RS 6000.   The operating system we delivered to IBM, they went on to call AIX, Advanced Integrated eXecutive, I guess.   It is still available from IBM.  

Today's email addressing system (name@server.domain) was not ubiquitous at the time.   I worked with Dan Franklin, who'd worked at Bolt Beranek and Newman (BBN) with [[Ray Tomlinson|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Tomlinson]], who died early this month (3/2016) and who's credited with that email domain addressing.    Up until that time (from Jan 1, 1970 which is  time = 0 in the unix world), the [[UUCP (Unix to Unix Copy Protocol)|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UUCP]] was, sort of, the standard.

So, an email address in the Unix world (i.e. Not IBM, digital, ARPA, ...) looked like    `...!ihnp4!sfmin!mjm`  which I think, in some ways makes a lot more sense.   since the address, like most number systems, had the most significant bits on the left, and the least significant on the right.    The way its read:   the "..." says "however you get to the internet backbone, since there was no DNS in those days, a sender had to now how to get from their computer to the "backbone", I'm asserting that I know "ihnp4" connects to the backbone, and also to a machine called "sfmin", and where my account is "mjm".   Basically, your system administrator had the job of maintaining the backbone connection(s) and telling their users what it was.   Not every machine was directly connected, so some paths might be longer.   It was possible to translate one system's email addressing scheme to another; the complexity is what forced the domain standard.

in the AT&T network, the exclamation was the only separator in an email address (other systems were thoughtlessly complex), and the user account was the last piece on the right.   so a friend whose address might be  ...!vaxpopuli!urcs2!band, would have me in his/her address book as   vaxpopuli!ihnp4!sfmin!mjm,    and he/her in mine would be ihnp4!vaxpopuli!urcs2!band.  The AT&T machines all carried the two-character building code, ih = Indian Hill (Illinois), sf = Summit Facility (NJ), and a particular machine, SF having "min" and "max"   The University of Rochester had a DEC VAX 780 as their ticket to "the bone", whimsically named VAXpopuli, suggesting the "Voice of the People".   

at home, Pat at UC Irvine in '74 when Chip was born, had brought home a set-up like the '84 video showed. The setup had a small tv monitor with a 16x64 character display, and an acoustic modem. which differed only from the video, that instead of flipping a switch on the modem, you'd put the handset into a pair of acoustic cups -- the audio was going directly thru the handset to get to the connection..   the software in the system, on screen, was basically what has been called a "bulletin board" since that time (late '70s) where you are only capable of connection to those with accounts on that machine --no wider network in that system.

Any self-respecting unix system had an "FTP" file-transfer protocol process to routinely ship files from computer to computer, again using the UUCP protocol.   In 1984, at INteractive Systems, we used it (I had set it up) to synchronize 120 developers at 4 sites across the US, working on the 1700 files which made up the Unix Kernel and uilitities,   The updates weren't real-time as they are today on sites like github. dropbox, google docs, ... we synchronized overnight. and resolved conflicts.   When we started, there were 200 file conflicts on the night we went live, so email was sent to the developers who'd worked on the same file  with instructions to "work it out" between themselves.  After two weeks there would be a handful of conflicts every night by which time, everyone knew just about who the other party was.   We had standards the developers could use to accommodate simultaneous development.   

Thanks for the video, http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=szdbKz5CyhA&sns=em






A letter to Dan Callahan, replying to a PPT he'd sent "How the Apostles Died"

! [[Ephesus and Montpelier]]

i spent two years in turkey with the DoD.  didn't know about Edessa.  but did visit Ephesus, and camped on the Turkish side just a stone's throw from Patmos.    there's the foundation of a 4th C cathedral in Ephesus, where the guide told us  the two tombs visible in the floor are alleged to have belonged to Mary and John.   one of the GI's along asked the guide if Mary had been assumed into heaven, why  did she have  crypt there?

and another note on Mary's life there.  there's a story about the German explorer, who in the late 19thC was picking his way thru the ruins, -- e.g. the temple of Artemis is there, an ancient wonder -- meanwhile a old woman back in Germany, never having been more than 40,50 k from home, had a vision of where to find Mary's last home.   The tour took us to the site;  it's not in the sweep of the digs at the time (50 yrs ago now), but wasn't more than 2k from the Agora, the market.   the site was acknowledged in a visit there by Paul VI as the "likely last home" of the BVM.

and while i'm riffing on Ephesus, I have a younger cousin who visited there in the last two years.   there are two greek amphitheaters there.   the one for staging plays seats shy of 1000.  the larger seats upwards of 20 - 25K.  St Paul undoubtedly spoke there.  In '68 when I was there, the speaker's stone was available to the tourists.  My cousin informed me that is no longer the case.   I was able to stand in the 2-3" deep impressions at the focal point of the theater.  One get's the impression you hardly had to raise your voice to reach the audience.


totally independent of ephesus, but the other "i've put my feet in history" moment was when Pat and I visited Monticello and Montpelier in rural VA about 5 yrs ago.   Montpelier was James Madison's home. he who drafted the constitution.   The guide on our tour pointed out Madison had done most of the work in his library where we standing.  In this case, I was standing on the spots where he'd spilled the ink.   Realizing that, I immediately hearkened back to standing where Paul had stood, and thinking, my footsteps in two foundational documents: Paul's epistles, and the US Constitution. 








Mark,

    Replying to your Sun 12/9 in the Op-Ed, I agree "I hope new historians treat him kindly". 

    I do take exception to your assertion the country turned it's back on "the greatest generation" because of James Carvil's lead "it's the economy, stupid".   Recall England rejecting the greatest hero of WWII, faster than a lit cigarette; the crowd needs to forget the horror. 

    It's the Bush failure to repudiate the Lee Atwater-promoted Willy Horton ad which did more to fragment the country than Bush's patrician attitude toward the people. It was more than "out of character".   And on we Democrat's side,  John Kerry was a zero-term president because of an equally patrician attitude toward the working man, more-so than the SwiftBoat ads.  Were I to reform campaign ads, a candidate (or issue advocacy group) would have to accept every ad as part of their campaign, and account for it among their donors, with people's names attached as the donor.

  While you correctly identify the beginning of vitriol with the Clinton Presidency, It needs better identification:  the Republicans were justifiably upset when Hillary identified "the vast RWC".   It indeed was, and is real.   The other reason for Clinton's impeachment was getting even for the Nixon Impeachment.  The intervening Democratic President -- James Earl Carter, while not Teflon, was squeaky clean.

  Bush's death and surrounding celebration will best be remembered for contrasts between his values and that of the current, and too very-Republican office-holder.

In reply to Mike McGowan:

> very nice, Mike!

> My Frank Robinson story.   Brendan can confirm the date, '67 - '68?

> The Headline:  Good friend Steve Anderson and I were at'' both games of the double header when Frank Robinson hit HR's # 499 and 500.''


> The rest of the story.   After that double header, and until the bunch of us (mcgowansbaseball) were at a game in the Tar-jay field, I _never_ left a ball game early.   The lesson I took from that O's - Tigers game (?, Ben help us out) was that "it ain't over till it's over".

> It was  a workday.  Steve and I worked at No Such Agency,  B&W Parkway, midway between those cities.  Steve, having grown up in Elmira NY, then an Os farm team had seen many of the Os come up, Boog, Brooks?, ... and was a big fan.   We knew Robinson, F, was on the 500 HR threshold, and felt obligated.   It was a weekday double-header, imagine that.   I don't think it was a late season make-up.    We couldn't leave work until 5 pm, about the time the games started.   We had it on the radio on my Beamer (a Frankfurt bought (9/15/69) zwie tousand und zwie). The pedal was at the metal, as we raced up the Parkway.  The O's came to bat.  Robinson hit #499.  -- //"We'll surely get to the ballpark (old Memorial Stadium) before his next at bat"//.   We did.

> Can't even remember who won that game.   The second seemed to belong to the visitors, who ended up winning that one.   Remember, this is the 2nd game, where the first had started at 5 pm.   So, with the Os down about 6 runs in the 8th, well after 11 pm, tomorrow being a workday, Robinson's 8th inning appearance produced nothing of note.   //"Well, Steve, that looks like our last chance to see # 500"//.   -- OK, Let's go home.    And the car radio was working.   Don't ya know it.  The Os staged a rally in the 9th, practically going thru the order.   Realizing that we were now too far to turn around -- gate control in the 9th of a 2-hdr was minimal -- we decided to take our lumps if Robinson (Frank) got to the plate again.   He did, and the rest is history.   The sad fact for Steve was that even with the rally, capped by the Robinson HR, the O's still lost.   A feeling which I couldn't muster any sentiment for.  

> So, the fine print for our headline is "// --- and saw neither of them//"

> That's my story and we're sticking to it.

> =*+[]+  Marty McGowan  908 230-3739
> 64 Diamond Spring Dr, Monroe Twp NJ 08831
> http://mcgowans.org/pubs/family

> p.s. the reason i'm thinking it was the '67-'68 seasons was a. No Such Agency sent me to Turkey in the spring of '69 and Steve and I had a falling out in '71 after I'd gotten back.  b.  therefore it had to have been my pre-Turkey days. The brief coda:   Now two married couples, he'd persuaded me I'd promised to show him the Boundary waters in a canoe.   on the last day, the way in, we were against strong headwinds.   With heightened concern for Pat's safety, I put my back into it,  and we pulled away from Steve and Nancy.   When they got to the dock, it was clear that our friendship was coming to an end.   We fell out of touch when we left for CA in > 2 yrs.

!!! NAME

    ftplib -- library of ftp_ functions to simplify command line FTP.    

!!! SYNOPSIS

```
    $ source ftplib          -- loads the library
    $ ftp_set user Site Port -- sets USER SITE PORT
    $ ftp_files              -- list "ftp-able" local files
    $ ftp_run                -- mputs files ... 
    $ ftp_help
    $ ftp_uploadlist  *.html -- files needing upload
    $ ftp_common             -- to server sub-directory

```

!!! DESCRIPTION

it supports simple update (MPUT) of local files to remote FTP server.

when run from the local directory containing the file ...s to transfer
to the remoteServer/remote/directory.  files are not queued for
transfer if they have not changed (are not newer) than the last update.

see the functions:

```
    ftp_{many,mputs,make,help}
```
from a single local directory, it is possible to send files to other
remote directories; the commands make no assumptions about parallel
directory structure on the server.

!!! FILES

* $HOME/tmp/script.ftp -- temporary ftp script
* $(home)/lib/ftp_map.txt -- commands to map local directory onto server sub-directory, as follows:

The //ftp_map// entry has two tab-separated fields, the first a path or directory name, the second a command to execute.  The records are scanned in order, the command from the first matching record is executed to return the name for the server's sub-directory.

This record shows a local directory //commonplace//, which itself is a sub-directory of //Dropbox//, and any of the commonplace sub-directories are parallel between the local file-system and the server.

```
commonplace     pwd | sed 's/.*Dropbox//'
```

A command may echo a path-name.

!! SEE ALSO

Work is in progress to develop [[a function|App from Lib]] which collects the missing functions into an app: e.g. `ftp_app`.   This feature converts the family name into a script, where all the sub-functions are the first argument.

Contact the [[author|MartyMcGowan]] for status.








For all the functions in the current environment, collect each date of last change.

The syntax for the date is a colon-comment in the shell, a `date` tag.

```
    : date: 2018-12-28;
```
and shown in the function:


```
fun_lastchange () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-12-27;
    shd_getdate | sed 's/: date:* //; s/;.*//' | sort -rk2 | printfirst
}

```

Here shd_getdate collects the date stamps supplied by shd_setdate.  The date is cleaned up, sorted in reverse time order, and the first occurrence of each name is printed.







!! [[Function or Alias]]

Functions can get too small, almost an alias. 

!!! synax learned

*default arguments
*alias advangate

!!! Alias

A quick review of an alias.   Aliases are used to shortcut frequent, and otherwise cumbersome-to-type at the keyboard.  A simple one to save reaching for the `-` (minus) key, as an argument flag:


```
$ alias ll="ls -l"    # used
$ ll

```

A problem arises here.   You might find the need for any number of arguments.  Having multiple aliases is fine, but i prefer command families be built with functions.  Much too much work for the Weekend Edition of @FunctionsShell.

Let's discover a cross-over point.   When an alias becomes more useful than the function.

!!! functions

I've an exercise in my book, [[Shell Functions|http://leanpub.com/shellfunctions]], where i step thru a sequence in making a function more robust. Here's the result:

```
$ fbdy () { declare -f ${*-fbdy}; }
$ fbdy
fbdy () 
{ 
    declare -f ${*-fbdy}
}
$
```

The function takes advantage of the default argument syntax:  `${*:- ... }`
where the command arguments are substituted for the ''$*''.   Lacking any arguments, the `... ` is substituted, in our case, the function name ''fbdy'' itself.  The thing to note about this function is the final ''*''.   In this case, the alias will do just as well.   And since this is a command line entry, the alias short-hand should be preferred:

```
$ alias ff="declare -f"
$ ff fbdy
```

!!! the alias practice

This should give you an appreciation how to develop and alias practice:


```
$ alias ga
alias ga='alias | grep '
$
$ ga backup
alias bbf='backup $(backup_files); chmod +x *lib'
alias lbf='llrt $(backup_files)'
$
$ alias sava
alias sava='(alias; echo alias) > ~/.alias.rc; alias'
$
```

Here ''ga'' stands for ''G''rep ''A'' lias, ''sava'' is ''SAV''e ''A''lias.  This latter saves all current aliases in the `~/.alias.rc` file. Sourceing in your profile is a good way to keep the aiiases loaded.

Strays are unloaded:

```
$ unset aliasa aliasb ...

```










The function to test, `fun_libr` is tested by it's companion, `fun_libr_test`.

!!! fun_libr
The fun_libr function returns the value of a library tag in its comment header. e.g.

 :  : libr: functionlib;

The purpose of this feature is to identify the library name, hence the location of a function which may be out for edit in another directory.  A command such as this will restore the function to it's rightful place:


```
    $ declare -f {function} >> $(which $(fun_libr {function}))

```

Other commands are available to eliminate redundant functions in a library.   Appending to the library is benign, since sourcing a library retains the last definition of the function, ignoring prior definitions.

!!! fun_libr_test
The fun_libr_test function specifies the results based on: 

* the number of arguments, 
* whether a first argument is a function or not, 
* the presence of a tag or not.  
It also tests the user setting the ENVIRONMENT variable `DEFAULT_LIBR`

[[Function_Testing_Code]] :

{{Function_Testing_Code}}
produces:

```
$ fun_libr_test
a fun_libr                         : 
b fun_libr noSuchFunction          : functionlib
c fun_libr noSuchFunction emptylib : functionlib
c fun_libr fun_libr_test           : functionlib
c fun_libr graf_tidy               : graflib
c fun_libr graf_tidy functionlib   : graflib
d fun_libr fun_libr_tagless foolib : functionlib
e fun_libr fun_libr_test retiredlib: functionlib
d fun_libr fun_libr_tagless        : barlib
```







```
fun_libr () 
{ 
    : returns a LIBR tag value of the Function or the default 2nd argument;
    : libr: functionlib;
    : ${DEFAULT_LIBR:=functionlib};
    : date: 2020-02-20;
    report_notargcount 1 $# && { 
        return 1
    };
    isfunction $1 || { 
        echo ${DEFAULT_LIBR};
        return
    };
    set -- $(shd_getlibr $1) ${DEFAULT_LIBR};
    trace_call $#: $*;
    [[ $# -gt 1 ]] && echo $2 || echo $1
}
fun_libr_test () 
{ 
    : date: 2020-02-20;
    function fun_libr_tagless () 
    { 
        : date: 2020-02-19 a tagless function;
        return
    };
    function fun_libr_local () 
    { 
        local class=$1;
        shift;
        printf "$class fun_libr %-24s: %s\n" "$*" $(fun_libr $*)
    };
    : test for different arguments;
    : a. 0 -- { blank };
    : b. * -- notfunction: .....: ${DEFAULT_LIBR};
    : c. * -- function .... +tag: value;
    : d. 1 -- function .... -tag: ${DEFAULT_LIBR};
    : e. 2 -- function libr -tag: libr;
    : ---------------------------------;
    : libr: functionlib;
    unset DEFAULT_LIBR;
    fun_libr_local a;
    fun_libr_local b noSuchFunction;
    fun_libr_local c noSuchFunction emptylib;
    fun_libr_local c fun_libr_test;
    fun_libr_local c graf_tidy;
    fun_libr_local c graf_tidy functionlib;
    fun_libr_local d fun_libr_tagless foolib;
    fun_libr_local e fun_libr_test retiredlib;
    setenv DEFAULT_LIBR barlib;
    fun_libr_local d fun_libr_tagless;
    unset fun_libr_{tagless,local}
}

```

My reflections on the just-deceased 41st President of the USofA: [[George H W Bush]]

Let me tell three personal stories w.r.t. #41.  I never met the man.   I've only seen one living president, Bill Clinton, and just missed another JFK, in Oct '63, a month before his assassination.

But this is about Bush 41.  I'm never a fan of Republicans, but it seems fair that the praises he's receiving are well deserved and point to the gentleman he's recognized as.  My stories are three: on meeting one of his advance men in '78, on seeing his opponent, Michael Dukakis in '88, and a few months later, about a now little reported speech he gave on Sept 7, 1988, kicking off his campaign just after Labor Day

!!! the 78 campaign

I was being recruited to run Jack Swigert (Apollo 13 astronaut)'s El Paso County, Colorado, campaign for US Senator from Colorado.   A friend ( in the local Polish Bund), Pat recalls a Springs Architect,  was the organizer.   The draw was a young fellow, "on my way to TX for the Bush '80 campaign".   That didn't pull me in, but the group met again, where I did get to meet Swigert, knees-to-knees in a huddle on what the race would be about.   I didn't reject the idea out-of-hand, but later confided to the organizer that, "this business about me being a Democrat, it's in deep.   Get out the Brillo, and start scrubbing that indelible mark on my soul.  Underneath you'll find 'Democrat' stenciled."   Pat and I did attend a huge fund-raiser in McNichols arena in Denver:  Bob Hope, Glen Campbell, Bonnie Rait, before I gave the official "no".   

!!! the 88 Campaign

Yet to see a living President, having seen candidates Humphrey, Goldwater, neither of whom made,  Mike Dukakis came to Linden when we lived in neighboring Cranford.   Here's a chance to get the girls, Maura and Katie, to see what my dad had grown up with, and me to a lesser extent.  The event was just after both conventions, so Dukakis and Bush were the nominees.  In a rope-line in the park, I found a spot to put the girls in front, and being young and cute, they were likely candidates for a hand-shake.  I can't remember if Maura was awestruck, or just curious.  Katie was not going to let the opportunity pass,   When Dukakis grabbed her hand, she politely noted, "Mr Dukakis, your eyelids are really Bushy".  He wasn't amused.   Katie recently told me that the choice of words was meant to call out his opponent.

!!! the Campaign Kickoff speech.

I've not heard this reported in the 30 years since, but on September 7th, 1988, the Wednesday after the traditional Labor Day Campaign kickoff, Bush delivered a speech, in which he (must have read, certainly not have thought of extemporaneously) delivered "September 7th, a date which will live in INFAMY, ..."  blinked and kept on going, realizing the speech-writer needed a history lesson.

The mental image i raised shortly after this was a two-frame political cartoon, the packed House Chamber, the date is Dec 8th or 9th, 1941, President Roosevelt addressing the Members.  The first frame we see two reporters at the back of the hall, looking over their shoulders, and focused on [[Roosevelt as he utters the famous words|http://time.com/4593483/pearl-harbor-franklin-roosevelt-infamy-speech-attack/]].  In the second frame, one reporter turns to the other and says,  "Remembered for all time.  Maybe, but I'll bet that it's confused by the time 'Bedtime for Bonzo's Ron Reagan's Vice President is running for the office"

I just completed a [[github exercise]], in a few hours spread over the last two days.

Thinking i might have notes in my Software Diary was taking more time than necessary, when it occurred to me I've got a link the [[Git Book|https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2]].  In working thru that yesterday with the real problem of the [[commonlib]] I discovered what I think is a real problem with the presentation.

I ended up posting a question on Google Forums, //'' what is the name of my REPO?''//.  In prior attempts at learning Git, i'd grabbed some command history an compared it to the sequence in the book.

The answer, not apparent when you create your first local repository is:

> your repository, being local doesn't have a neme.  it just "is", like sitting in the directory you initialized with `git init`.   The REPO is best thought of a a Remote Repository. 

Go to (or create) your login account on github, and poke around to create your remote repository.  You can have many.  Then issue the command I've highlighted in the  GithubHistoryLesson.

What's important is the function i used to gather it:

```
marty3.$ git status -s -b
## master
marty3.$ set git_sum; ff $1; set $($1); diff $*; llrt $*; wc $*; ea
git_sum () 
{ 
    set $HOME/lib/git_sum.{txt,nxt};
    [[ -f $1 ]] || { 
        touch $1
    };
    { 
        cat $1 <(gh git | awk '$2 ~ /git/ && !p[$3,$4,$5]++' )
    } | sort -u > $2;
    echo $*
} 
80a81,82
>  1085  git status -s -a
>  1086  git status -s -b
-rw-r--r--  1 applemcg  staff  2537 Oct  8 12:51 /Users/applemcg/lib/git_sum.txt
-rw-r--r--  1 applemcg  staff  2585 Oct  8 14:57 /Users/applemcg/lib/git_sum.nxt
      80     398    2537 /Users/applemcg/lib/git_sum.txt
      82     408    2585 /Users/applemcg/lib/git_sum.nxt
     162     806    5122 total
2 /Users/applemcg/lib/git_sum.txt /Users/applemcg/lib/git_sum.nxt
marty3.$ 
```
Last things first.   the nxt file has two more lines than the text file,and two hours newer than its txt confederate.   The diff shows two status requests.   A look at the code shows how it's collected.  A gh command Greps the History (see the difference after the '80a81,82' the first field is the command number next the git command followed by its arguments.  in the awk script, tallying the 2nd, 3rd and 4th fields captures only the first appearance of a command and it's first two argument. the current history, and any subsequent would be concatenated but for  command line numbers.   this has the effect of eliminating duplicates whose commands are still within the 'history window'

As the file names have been set to the positional parameters, then  it's only necessary to occasionally:

$ mv $2 $1

Now go and take a look at the  GithubHistoryLesson, the complete record in git_sum.txt  until now.

```
date_stamp () 
{ 
    : date: 2020-02-02;
    for i in {1..1800};
    do
        date +%F,%H:%M:%S;
        sleep 1;
    done
}

```

HitlersLastPlot, a [[book by Sayer and Dronfield,|https://www.librarything.com/work/22680175/book/170818578]] follows events in the Third Reich's last month.  It's a tale of the //Prominenten//, 139 special prisoners of the SS.  They were to be used as bargaining chips as the Nazi regime collapsed.   Whether or not any would survive was unclear to all but a few of them, that mostly due to an unbelievably hopeful nature.

For me, two things stand out.  The book stops at all the concentration camps from which the special prisoners were collected and moved through to their //Alpine Fortress// redoubt.  That one of them, Dachau, holds special significance, as I visited there in late September '68 with my parents, Marty Jr and Betty McGowan. More on that in the following paragraph.   The other, more easily dealt with is the famous quote, now often mangled: //first they came for ..., and I did not speak out ... then they came ...//, and so on.  Here it is in it's entirety, quoted from page 122 in the book.

> First they came for the Socialists, and I did not speak out -- Because I was not a Socialist.
> Then they came for the Trade Unionists, and I did not speak out -- Because I was not a Trade Unionist.
> Then they came for the Jews, and I did not speak out -- Because I was not a Jew.
> Then they came for me -- And there was no one left to speak for me.

This was later written by Martin Niemoller, one of the //Prominenten//, a Lutheran pastor, who had "served as a  U-boat commander in the previous  war".   I'm of course, taken by both the inspiring quote, but the opportunity to riff on a shared first name . 


And a side note.  This book will receive commentary in my companion blog: [[TTGL]].

[[HS Lahman]]

To get the ball rolling, let me quote from HS (few knew him as anything but) Lahman, fraternity brother at MIT's [[PKT, Mass Eta chapter|http://pkt.mit.edu/about/]].  This from his [[The College Years|https://hslahman.com/the-college-years/]], where under College Perspectives, he offers this undoubtedly true - you don't make this stuff up - story.

> ''Never Believe What People Tell You''. P7 was an EE who missed his calling. He should have been in sales because he could sell snake oil to anyone. During a snow storm he was bored, so he called an employment agency and demanded to know where the snow shovelers were. He represented himself as a Mass DPW supervisor. He then called the DPW, using the employment agency guy’s name wanting to know where the snow shovelers should go. Then he bounced back to the employment agency using the name of the guy he talked to at the DPW. It took a couple of more calls, but eventually he got jobs for twenty snow shovelers in Copley Square.

It should be explained that P7 is "pledge # 7"  (or is it person #7), granted anonymity at the request of //The Twit//, whose identity is revealed within a few paragraphs.

In full disclosure, my acquaintance with HS may be inferred from the range of his tales.   He was in a 5 - 6 year program at MIT which facilitated his sage wisdom becoming available to classes beyond the normal undergraduate span.






Today begins what I believe is my final turn in blogging. In literary terms, //I believe I've found my pen//.

Today, I'm commenting on an opinion piece in today's NY Times by [[David Reich|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Reich_(geneticist)]], the subject is [['Race' in the age of Modern Genetics|https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/23/opinion/sunday/genetics-race.html]]

I'm in complete agreement with Reich's proposal in this article, which concludes with:

> It is important to face whatever science will reveal without prejudging the outcome and with the confidence that we can be mature enough to handle any findings. Arguing that no substantial differences among human populations are possible will only invite the racist misuse of genetics that we wish to avoid.

Reich speaks to both sides of the divide on the subject of 'race'. Since most of the Times audience probably identifies as liberal, he cautions against the "social construct" argument. Ta-Nehisi Coates captures the point with "Race is the child of racism, not its parent". Reich summarizes Richard Lewontin's data from 1972, where Lewontin

> found that around 85 percent of variation in the protein types could be accounted for by variation //within// populations and "races", and only 15 percent by variation //across// them.

Then to make his stronger point, against the racist misrepresentation of the facts:

> One of Mr Wade's sources, for example is the anthropologist, Henry Harpending, who has asserted that people of sub-Saharan African ancestry have no propensity to work when they  don't have to because, he claims, they did not go through the type of natural selection for hard work in the last thousands of years that some Eurasians did.

I quote the following, only as a //note to self// to recall thoughts I was having in reading his full article.

> Another high-profile example is James Watson, the scientist who in 1953 co-discovered the structure of DNA, and who was forced to retire as head of the Cold Spring Harbor Laboratories in 2007 after he stated in an interview -- without any scientific evidence -- that research has suggested that genetic factors contribute to lower intelligence in Africans than in Europeans.

The thought I was having when I read this was //now where did I read about the eugenics craze in the 30s at that lab on Long Island?// Reich's reference to Watson refreshed my memory.  The story is in Brenda Maddox' [[Rosalind Franklin: The Dark Lady of  DNA|http://www.librarything.com/work/83263/summary/122035764]].
My recollection was of eugenics work done at the laboratory through the '30s with evidence found here under [[Founding and early years|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cold_Spring_Harbor_Laboratory]]. In reading //Franklin//, there was evidence of Third Reich (Nazi) visits to the laboratory, where "science", of the type Reich warns against legitimized that regime's Holocaust.

With his reference to Watson's views, Reich is surely aware of the dark history of the laboratory thru the '30s.  He may have omitted the Nazi connection realizing it's inflammatory nature.  Interested parties should follow references to the [[Eugenics Record Office|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugenics_Record_Office]] and
[[The ERO at Cold Spring Harbor, 1910-1940: An Essay in Institutional History|https://www.jstor.org/stable/301835]].

In a later post, I'll take up the framework for this new thread.







A letter to a book club friend:  I'm replying to an Economist article he'd recently given me.

-----

A quick read of the [[subject paper|https://www.economist.com/leaders/2019/11/28/inequality-could-be-lower-than-you-think]] prompts this reply, but after you take a quick look at today's [[NYTimes op-ed by Anand Giriharadas|https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/21/opinion/sunday/billionaires-inequality-2020-election.html]].   Look for the quote on socialism: the generational perspective.  It might help you overcome your too-hasty response to the challenge, "what's so bad about socialism"


After the Piketty reference, concluding the next paragraph, we see:

<<<
In Denmark, one of the few places with detailed data, the wealth share of the top 1%  has not risen for three decades.  By contrast, few deny that the richest Americans have sprinted ahead.  But even here, wealth is fiendishly difficult to estimate.
<<<

My margin quote is "and why, I might ask?"


First answer, "there is no one with sufficient motivation, ( ~ compensation ) to accurately answer that".
To which I'd repeat my challenge, "Why ... ?"


Next, I find it inconceivable that with much wealth tied up in reasonably liquid assets:  equities, debt,  there is no one south of (pick a number, say $100 M) that couldn't tell you how much they're worth within, say 10%.


The "fiendishly difficult" is at best a smoke screen.  Talk about _all_ the other asset classes, like say art, commodity futures,  ....   Those less frequently traded, art e.g. have historic trajectories.   If that Matisse hasn't been traded in, say 35 years, i'll bet Christie's would be able to put a price on it, for a price, of course.


To me, the "fiendishly" argument is a huge red herring.  e.g. the parenthetical remark in the next following paragraph removes any uncertainty on my part: "investor's wealth they report to the taxman".


What I recall from Piketty, the biggest challenge to calculating net wealth has more to do with its distributed nature, --- e.g. off-shore banks and investments, and the respective sovereign's who are in thrall to corporation assets in their domain.  His solution: international standards, and open banks.


I'd like to thank you for such a simple send-up.   I'll get around to the others in good time


~ signature ~


p.s. sorry, in searching for the reason for the "still plenty to do .. " subtitle,  i'd overlooked the article continued, onto the next page, where we see this one:

<<<
... too many high income workers, including doctors, lawyers and bankers, are protected from competition by needless regulation... which should be loosened.
<<<

My experience with the legislative process is that most regulations are written by lawyers,  and a fair bit of that is to be self-sustaining.   The verbal stretch, conflating "high income" and "workers" triggers a this-statement-demands-scrutiny response.








This is [[the intro|Intro_SF]] to A Simple Function, which has become [[An Expensive Lesson]]

The object here, first, is to acquire skills to turn command-line sequences into functions, and then to solve a specific problem.  

In full disclosure, the idea to create a function occurred after having worked out the sequence at the command line.  

!!! skills acquired:

* command history collected into a function -- //function () {// !NNN; ... //; }//
* online function edit -- ''sed''
{{Skills to Acquire}}

First note how the history may be turned into a function.   Simply typing the selected command numbers: `!NNN;` in succession collects the commands.   

Next, the ''sed'' to replace //confict// and //conflicted// shows how to convert the specific into the general.    

As it turns out, the `.conflict` could have been well-replaced by `.tmp`, thus rendering the argument list to just the files of interest, and no need for the special `${*:N}` syntax.

A side-effect-free testcase is supplied to establish the value of the method, and increase user confidence.

!!! problem statement

{{Software Tic}}

!!! and Lesson

[[An Expensive Lesson]]

The grey lining in the cloud is these lessons, while good in general, were practiced on the wrong example. 

In an attempt to DRY out, i should have taken the Chess-player's advice:   i//f the move looks too good, you can afford to sit on your hands. //

I have trouble getting into novels. Any Novel.   Some authors I give wide berth, others not so.   Now reading Laura Lippman's [[Lady in the Lake|https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41735375-lady-in-the-lake]], and like 3/4 of the novels i read, on a Kindle.   In my case an old Paperwhite, 1st Generation according to [[this note|https://blog.the-ebook-reader.com/2015/07/01/how-to-tell-kindle-paperwhite-generations-apart/]].   A few months back, considering a trade-in (Amazon offers $25 for this model)  I decided to keep it, as its text-search feature distinguishes the e-reader from the paper copy.

How does this help a novel-challenged reader?   Lady in the Lake is my first Lippman encounter, and I want to make it an honest one.   Bob Johnson, back in '64 observed, "New York [city] is like a book.  You don't need more than 5 minutes to decide if you want to stay longer".  This book offers the exception to the rule.  In this case the setting -- Baltimore --and the time -- late '60s.   Simultaneous connections on life's road.

What happens?  How does the Kindle raise the experience?  My reading habits aren't the best; I have trouble focusing.   I'm rotating Lady in the Lake, chapters at a time each, with Isaacson's Einstein bio and ~McKibben's "Falter".   So the lady is competing with two books where my focus more easily gained.   [[This morning|2019-08-11, Sunday]], opening to chapter four, I'm thinking "I have no feel for this character yet.  I think she's the protagonist, but I'd flunk a spot quiz about any aspect of her life".   So, I search for "Maddie", about her only recognizable feature, and vowing to start where she picks up.   

Voila!!  I haven't wasted that much yet, and re-tracing from the earliest paragraphs has stenciled her character into my view of the scene.   What did I learn about why I wasn't able to focus?   My hasty reading had failed to detect the important feature of this work:  there's more than one narrator, three by this point: Maddie, and after a dinner party, Wally, a high-school prom date, now a Baltimore TV personality, and Judith, daughter of a family jewelry store, where Maddie goes to trade-in a wedding ring.  

It's likely I'll have to use the search and restart model again in reading a novel.  Other common literary devices will likely expose other lessons to learn.  To do that, [[It Takes a Kindle]]

[[Joe Pavlichko]] died [[yesterday|29th March 2019]]. He defined "good guy", with so much of the stuff he found it easy to share, or maybe difficult to avoid sharing.

Here's [[Joe's Obiturary|https://rezemfh.com/tribute/details/1673/Joseph-Pavlichko/obituary.html]]

When I met his wife Deb, Joe introduced me as "one of the good guys".   I can accept the accolade, since he so personified the concept, that it was flattering to be a class with Joe.   He didn't abuse the effect.  

His great contribution to Stonebridge was the Men's Club Golf Outing.  While the amount isn't the most important thing about his contribution, the proceeds from this and the Men's Club Community calendar, also a Joe-run event, raised most of our charitable donation funds.  And he did it with commitment suffused with passion and joy.    Anyone who was drawn in, as I was this last year on the calendar, did it as much for the camaraderie as some sort of "it's good to do good" goal.  The real "let's do it in the community" sense.  As much the "how" as the "what" or "how much money".

Joe, while not on the Men's Club Board, was a key member of the Fundraising Committee, headed by a VP of Fundraising.  I don't know that Joe ever held that title.   It's going on a year since I was the Club Secretary, which gave me this insight:  the "success" metric is how many recent officers are still active by contributing to the board and necessarily the whole club.  Joe recruited our current President.  And with a most able Activities VP have led the club to it's two most successful  years, at least in my now six years in the community of twelve years.   A signal event was a members survey Joe put together at the now two years on Holiday Party.    We  implemented as many suggestions as would fit on the calendar.

My one regret was never having made it to the golf outing.   This reminds me of a lesson learned at "uncle" John McGowan's funeral:  life is short: do it now, whatever "it" is.

After stepping aside from the term-limited board position, I've enjoyed keeping the untitled role of "recorder" of the Men's Club General meeting. I've enjoyed the reporting role, and try to produce a product worthy of my father's and grandfather's praise.   Joe's notice of the work has been a sufficient surrogate.

While shopping today I recalled his spirit guiding me: it's in the daily events we carry the gifts we're received to others.   The poor guy at the check-out next to me might have used a good-guy's help, but seemed out of reach of my abilities to calm the waters.

Good night Mrs Calabash, wherever you are.

[[Early Middle Ages]]: [[Justinian and the Byzantine Empire]]

!!! The Eastern Empire.

* held until 1453, by the Turks
* "Byzantine" adj: devious
* term aroze in 16th, 17th C
* was founded on Byzantium
* however 'we are the Romans' 
* continuity, from the whole Roman empire
* to differentiate, B is worth it because of language.
* Greek died in west in 4th ... C. 
* B. reverted to Greek.  by 600, all law in G.
* Odoacer, 476 didn't rile the East.

!!! Justinian 

* tried to reconquer Italy  527-565
* pol disaster,  attempt to overthrow by "chariot hooligans":  'blues' vs 'greens'
* brawls, turn unity in 532, 
* wife, theodora advised massacre
* peace w/ Persians, 532
* first, vandal N. Africal 533 by bribing Sicilian vandal
* vandals absorbed by 534
* next: ostrogoth North Italy, Q. Amalasuntha
* maybe peaceful reunion
* Q. A. accepted theodahad, and was murdered
* therefore J invaded O.I  Genl Belasarious pushed OG north of the Po Valley
* J didn't see Persian threat
* Per recaptured Eastern, and J sent G.B to repel
* 542, Justinian plague 1st plague instance, recurred every decade
* Popl declined by 33% in two decades
* 14 more years of war, on O's
* lots of destruction in Italy, Roman Senate fell

!!! eliminate paganism

* platonic academy came to an end
* //the secret hisotry//, by procopius, Secy to G Belasarious,
* gruesome hatchette job against J and Theodora
* treaty of eternal peace 532
* forbade teaching philosophy in Athens 529
* reconstructed of Hagia Sophia 532-537
* to exceed grandeur of temple of solomon
* recodificaiton of roman law
* smuggle silkworms out of china
* net, net, did more harm than good.
* left empire weaker
* post death, lost part of N, Italy
* Lombards appeared in 568, taking N.I.

!!! post Justinian

* Slavs appeared, established permanent in Balkans, 580s.
* Were pushed out of Greece, held Bal
* 610s, persians siezed Egypt, modern Turkey
* Byz lost "true cross" to Persions
* 620s with Avars, Slavs, Persians, all but Constantinople , 
* city of C was most defensible, on a spit of land.
* Persians were repelled 628, from Asia Minor
* Regained Relic of True Cross

!!! conclusion

* greek langauge
* survived West by 1000 years
* conquest attempts overtaxed Eastern

* WB Yeats poem, from Colm Toibin's //Mad, Bad, Dangerous to Know//, p. 167, WB Yeats, //For Old Age//

```
    I pray -- for fashion's word is out
    And prayer comes round again --
    That I may seem, though I die old,
    A foolish, passionate man.
```
* Samuel Taylor Coleridge, concluding lines from  //A Child's Evening Prayer//, public domain, discovered [[TWA -- The Writer's Almanac|http://www.garrisonkeillor.com/radio/twa-2018-the-writers-almanac-for-january-4-2019/]]

```
    may we always love each other,
    Our friends our father, and our mother:
    And still, O Lord, to me impart
    An innocent and grateful heart,
    That after my last sleep I may
    Awake to thy eternal day!
        Amen.

```

Writes a function into its family library.

Functions named {fam}_function are stored in {fam}lib.

```
libcmd () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-12-01;
    set ${1%_*}lib $*;
    shd_setdate ${*:2} | tee -a $(which $1)
}

$ libcmd acct_active  # for example
```
The `acct_active` function is written into its'' acctlib''

This note improves shell library finding in two ways:

* local libraries needn't be on the users PATH, and
* the PATH needn't be adorned with any ../../bin directories.

{{bitmeld}}

presented here are a few functions which:

* find the nearest bitmeld in the directory tree,
* list the nearby [[Local Libraries]]
* demonstrate a simple usage

!! Demonstration

First, list the functions:

```
$ declare -f llibs bitmeld booklib
llibs () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-07-27;
    case $# in 
        0)
            set echo $(bitmeld)
        ;;
        *)
            set "$1" $(bitmeld)
        ;;
    esac;
    $1 $2/bin/*lib
}
bitmeld () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-07-14;
    case $PWD in 
        /)
            return
        ;;
    esac;
    for d in bin inc include tmp man etc lib doc;
    do
        [[ -d $d ]] && { 
            echo ${1:-.} $PWD $d;
            return
        };
    done;
    indir .. bitmeld ${1:-.}/..
}
booklib () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-07-28;
    llibs | grep $(myname)
}
$ bitmeld               # relative, absolute, bitmeld member

./.. /Users/applemcg/Dropbox/shellfunctions/manuscript bin
$
$ booklib               # here it is
./../bin/booklib

$ source $(booklib)     # loads the functions
$ functions  $(booklib) #lists them
book_history
incl
capfun
finincl
funthruch
ctob
chno
tomd
forgetlib
booklib
funfiles
loclib
libshere
comprlib
prepmake
local_refs
extract_new
$
```

!! Assessment

These functions assist my editing, proofing, table-making, for my forthcoming update to Shell Functions.   They might be interesting at a later date.  But here, they are readily available without needing to be on my PATH environment variable.   Time to clean that up.

It's worth a mention that llibs has what i call the //smart-function// property:  arguments to the function become a command:

```
$ llibs "ls -l"
-rwxr-xr-x@ 1 applemcg  staff  2530 Jul 28 14:14 ./../bin/booklib
chap01.$ 
```

Maria Metzler Johnson died [[today|2019-11-25, Monday]].   We learned of her death [[later|2019-12-05, Thursday]].

Her [[obituary is here|https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/statesman/obituary.aspx?n=maria-johnson&pid=194591083&fhid=5106]]

We share two major moments,  events in our lives. And though early in life, we remained in touch thru annual Christmas letters, and recently, 2017, a visit to their (hers and Calvin's) Austin home.

I took Maria to her Junior Prom (fall 1965?).   As i reconstruct how that happened and what we did, it's long-since escaped my memory, other than it was with her room-mate, I had my first serious love.  A very few years later, when I met Pat (6/13/69), it was the "house" party.  Pat was planning a trip to Europe with her new roommate in the fall, including the October-fest.    Her new roommate, also NSA employee, was Maria!   Since a friend, Ed Walker, at our Turkish outpost, Sinop on the Black Sea,  was to be my traveling companion, "that's perfect".  

 I don't remember too many details, but since Pat and I were engaged in Zurich on 9/14, I'd alerted Ed to my plan to ask for Pat's hand that evening. I recall the restaurant, many Turks at our table, how about if Pat and I duck out separately.  So possibly we, Maria and I didn't get to share many moments there after.    We'd rendezvoused in Milan, at Fran Craig's apartment, traveled to Zurich, Basel, Paris, and did make it down to Munich.   The memory of Paris, looking for two rooms, the clerk asked us how were were paired, Ed with Pat or Maria, and Marty vice-versa.   "No, it's Ed and Marty, Pat and Maria".   To which, when the joke appeared in a notable magazine, the reply was "This isn't that kind of place".

Sorry to see you go, Maria. Be assured, the memories are fond. Particularly to pass that day at your place, and for me, us, to witness the full spirit you possessed, shared, and being present to your guests, one last time. 







[[Markdown]]

In the beginning, there was TiddlyWiki,  but when I discovered [[Markdown|https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/]], I was hooked.  It's easy conversion of text to the HTML file was what I needed. I've been thru a circle (see the [[Commonplace book|http://mcgowans.org/pubs/marty3/commonplace/]] discussion) of Markdown formats, and in the last two weeks settled on the original Gruber Markdown.

I use Markdown to deliver the [[Stonebridge|http://rcpcommunities.com/stonebridge/home.asp]] Men's Club General Meeting Minutes, and the Board Meeting Minutes.   Gruber's Makdown has a few advantages over ~OrgMode, and other Markdown formats ([[Commonmark|http://commonmark.org/]], and Pandoc's [[markdown variant|https://rmarkdown.rstudio.com/authoring_pandoc_markdown.html#markdown_variants]]).  Principally, it's ability to embed HTML tags, e.g. IMG,  with a minimum of effort. 

My Markdown output is destined for PDF files, a public record which, if needing modification,  is amended in a future club minutes, ...

In this way, my Markdown usage differs from ~OrgMode.   Markdown output is for today, the record of reference.  ~OrgMode, for the ages, is for continual revision.

And before moving on, my e-book [[Shell Functions|http://leanpub.org/shellfunctions]] is written with Markdown






This is under development since 5/7/2018.

The family view spreadsheet has two worksheets.  The first, ~MartyPat, described here shows our current holdings, and [[Recommendation]], which lists the equities, ETFs and Funds I regularly evaluate.

~MartyPat has two sections, those which should be sorted together, and the remainder, whose functions follow the first group.

!!! these columns must be sorted together

see the discussion at the end of this group.

*symbol -- the market ticker name of the stock
*w -- for Who: m for Marty,  p for Pat, tests column G, "basis" if Marty holds any, otherwise Pat
*sector -- 1 thru 5 for CalandrosTable of industry sectors. a vlookup on the [[Recommendation]], table of various recommendation  sources
*type: equity, spec, invest, cash, bond.  where //equity// are allocated according to CalandrosTable, //spec// on recommendations from Bill D,  //invest// are some stocks, and a few funds for diversity, and all lightly traded held for some time, //cash// is on account or unsettled trades, and //bond// is  an aggregate of our bond ladders.
*nth -- a one-up count of stocks in the sector,  in increasing order of holding.  Note that while Marty's start with 1, Pat's start with the next after Marty's highest number, together, these produce the //sort// column value
*marty, basis: the number of shares he owns, and the Fidelity-reported cost for all the shares, the weighted cost, given the various purchase and sales
*pat, basis: same for her shares
*monthly: the closing price on a month-end Friday.   If the last day of the month is a Monday or Tuesday, it's the prior Friday, otherwise, the following Friday, which will be the 1st, 2nd, or 3rd of the next month.  this field is redundant since Pat and I now all hold separate stock.  in the beginning it was the weighted basis of our combined holdings.  and now duplicated in a subsequent column.
*sort:  the number in the 2nd row (now 11), is the maximum number in the nth column. Chosen so the formula `max(nth) * (sector - 1) + nth `guarantees unique and ascending numbers for the column.   To re-prioritize the holdings, swap a pair of numbers in a sector. and this is the fun part:  

    # select from the column header: //symbol// thru //sort//
    # holding the mouse button down, sweep thru the last symbol, e.g. //bond//
    # then menu >> Data >> Sort Range .. >> [ ] has header row >> sort by: select "sort", and
    # voila, the symbols are re-odered.

!!!columns which depend on the prior set
*who: recommended the stock, FYB -- Calandro, mm -- , BILL -- my guy
*risk: for the stocks the Motley Fool recommends, their risk assessment. Smaller is less risky.
*life:  the percentage gain  `(price/life basis) - 1`
*month: same for the month basis
*day: same for today: `(price/closeyest) - 1`
*life: either the marty or pat basis
*closeyest: ` =googlefinance(symbol,"closeyest")`
*price: same, i.e. `=googlefinance(symbol,"price")`
*today:  e.g. `marty hold * (price - closeyest)`

!!! [[Dan|https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/McGowan-479]]'s email

Good stuff, Marg—so the Federal Food Admin job obviously didn’t come with any kind of draft deferment.  And in that 1917-18 era [[Grandpa|https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/McGowan-727]] wasn’t running the Press alone was he?  Although didn’t all the McGowan boys eventually have to report for WWI duty?  Wasn’t there an edition of the Pioneer Press that had pictures of all 5 of them across the top of the front page?

!!! Meg's reply
I haven’t seen the Pioneer Press article about Sarah McGowan’s sons.  It was published about Aug or Sept 1918 and later cited in a Victory edition of the Appleton Press in Dec. 1918.  I have the Press page for the McGowans (and the [[Vieg|https://www.wikitree.com/genealogy/VIEG]]s).  

* [[Allen|https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/McGowan-889]] McGowan was running the Press as managing editor while the rest of the brothers were in the service.  I read some issues he put out during one of my trips to the MN History Center.  He was quite critical of local men who tried to avoid the draft, including one editorial on Art Krebs, who was being helped to avoid being drafted by his brother C. M. Krebs, as I recall.
*[[Joe McGowan |https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/McGowan-770]]was the first of the brothers to enlist in July 1917 about three months after the US entered the war, and was in training with the medical corps in New Mexico from Sept 1917 for about a year.  He arrived in France just before the armistice was signed in Nov. 1918, but didn’t get released until Jan. 1919.  
* [[Pat|https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/McGowan-891]] enlisted, also in the medical corps, in Dec 1917, was posted at Ft. Snelling for several months, and actually made it to France a couple months before Joe.  Although he didn’t work at the Press, 
* [[John |https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/McGowan-891]]was third to enlist in April 1918 and went into Air Transport, and was still in officer candidate training in Virginia when the war ended.  Leo went to Annapolis in  June 1917 and was on the USS Missouri in the summer of 1918. 
* Allen did register for the draft.  Perhaps having several brothers already in service helped him in  not getting called up.

The McIII index is a weighted composite of the now widely reported indices/averages:

*Dow Jones Industrial Average
*The S&P 500 Index,
*The NASDAQ Composite, and
*The Russell 2000 index

Prior to last week, I wasn't including the Russell 2K (RUT), but thought it couidn't hurt, and lo and behold the major market new outlets, CNBC and Bloomberg have taken to include when they show the others on the same panel.

I sort the percentage movement for the day from lowest to highest, and weight the terms in that order, by 1, 3, 3, 1 and divide the product by 8.   The mathematically inclinded will recognize these as the fourth set of binomial coefficients, arising from Pascal's triangle, which looks like this:

```
           1
         1   1
       1   2   1
     1   3   3   1
      . . . . . . 
```
The second row gives you the clue for the general pattern.  The //average// is calculated by ` ( 1 * x + 1 * y ) / 2`.  For four sorted numbers: a, b, c, d, the equivalent is 

```
(1*a + 3*b + 3*c + 1*d) / ( 1+3+3+1 ) = (a + 3b + 3c +d)/8
```

For instance, here's the action at 3:30 PM EST 3/23/2018, another particularly down day.   The weighted average, //wavg// is the day's change in the McIII.  Another day, the indices or averages may sort differently.

```
-1.386%	 -1.619%  -1.436%  -1.356%     -1.098%
wavg      Nasdaq   S&P 500  Russell 2K    DJI
          bottom    3rd       2nd         top
            1       3          3           1
```








Two functions [[median_opens]] and `daily_open`

```
median_opens () 
{ 
    : doc: from the daily_open log, report successive median times,;
    : +: from the odd-numbered leading samples, pick the median record;
    : +: after a sort on the hh:mm:ss, the 5th field..;
    : record: 2019-05-03 Fri May 03 08:42:14 daily_reading ...;
    : vars: max, med, cut;
    : max = half the number of lines, rounding an even number down to the odd;
    : med = 1, 2, 3, 4, ... max, the median record of;
    : cut = 1, 3, 5, 7, ......., N records;
    : note: this approach highlights bash arithmetic, where a proper, scalable;
    : +: solution would be done entirely in awk, sorting an internal array.;
    : +: also, when I get to working on bash tags, the leading characters in;
    : +: these non-executing comment lines, I have just invented the "note" tag.;
    : date: 2019-05-09;
    set -- $(wc -l $(home)/lib/daily_open.log);
    : trick: set arguments -- 1st = number of lines, 2nd is the data file.;
    (( max = ($1+1) / 2 ));
    (( med = 1 ));
    while (( med <= max )); do
        (( cut = 2*med - 1 ));
        sed ${cut}q $2 | sort -k5 | awk "NR == $med { print \$5 }";
        (( med += 1 ));
    done
}
daily_open () 
{ 
    : both USCCB audio,text BIBLE readings and WRITERS ALMANAC;
    : date: 2019-04-02;
    set writers_almanac morning_offering papal_intention daily_{audio,reading};
    foreach smart_open $*;
    pptlog smart_open $*
}

```

```
mkdir_test () 
{ 
    : tests the MKDIR FUNCTION against the man page;
    : the principle is the binary does not need flags.;
    : date: 2020-03-04;
    function _clean_foo () 
    { 
        : app_trace $*;
        [[ -d foo ]] || return;
        find foo | xargs ls -ld;
        rm -fr foo
    };
    function _announce () 
    { 
        printf "\n-----\n$1\n"
    };
    function _test_case () 
    { 
        : app_trace $*;
        _announce "$1";
        mkdir ${*:2};
        _clean_foo
    };
    _clean_foo;
    :;
    _test_case "no flags, just directories" foo/bar/zot;
    :;
    _test_case "the -p flag and directories" -p foo/minusP/zot;
    :;
    _test_case "the -v flag and directories" -v foo/minusV/zot;
    :;
    _test_case "the -m mode and directories" -m 550 foo/mode/550;
    :;
    _announce "All Clear";
    _clean_foo;
    unset _clean_foo _test_case _announce
}

```
