n this period of [[Time On Your Hands]] TOYH, i had a mental
phenomenon we all must often encounter: that of a random thought or
memory triggered by a seemingly disconnected stream of thought
itself.

In my case, at the moment, 6:20 am on Friday, march 27, in Monroe
township NJ, while putting together the acronym of this note, TOYH,
the random thought was parking a rental car at my brother Kevin's
apartment complex in Tucson AZ.  Just pulling into a covered spot, Pat
with me. In the passenger seat.  And sort of a removed-from-body
view : looking at the car from behind on and  the
passenger side, maybe a foot or two from coming to a stop as I was
driving.

I was assembling the acronym in my head T O Y H. In my head, thinking
of how to present it for a readership.

And the image of parking the car appeared.  I think it was dark —
black maybe.  Pat didn’t get out of the car, the scene was more
like a GIF image: two seconds of slight motion.

Meanwhile, what was it that required an acronym.  T O Y H.  Time On
Your Hands in this time of self-quarantine and social-distancing.

The time on my hands came after viewing an NYC-Arts production with
Paula Zahn showcasing the the Jewish Holocaust Museum on PBS 13 .
The special centered on an exhibit: too ... Not  long Ago, Not
 Far Away, about the horrors of the Auschwitz-Birkenau
extermination camps of the Nazis in WWII.

She featured a handful of survivors of the camps, book-ended by two
principal figures of the museum: Bruce Ratner and Ron Lauder.  They
are both contemporaries of min , plus or minus a year.  Metro NYC,
money, and dedicated to the preservation of memories wrapped in the
clothing of the Holocaust.

On to the thought: after the show concluded, credits rolled, I thought
about my time in the area —- battery Park, six years on state street
and my time in “the City:, what better way to refresh those moments
than with a t.  peek into the New Yorker Today app on this iPad.  An
article “The Trump o-clock follies” by. Susan B Glasser gave added
currency to the word “mendacious”

I think in know what that means, but lets check..  So a browse”
dictionary:mendacious” produced a list lead by dictionary dot com and
Merrimack Webster.  My age prejudices led my to the second on the
list: Merrimack-Webster; definition #2: telling a lie.  that’s easy
enough.  “He’s lying”.  So too said dictionary.co.  Posing the
question, which of those prominent authorities should I prefer?  what
else are they offering to keep me attracted.  Plot spoiler: Merrimack
Webster.  Why?

It was in the added attractions where they shined in my eyes.  They
offered a history of the word, in this case mendacious.  It first
appeared in print in the 16th century.  offering ... ( They both
... In addition th the historical reference, m/w offered scans of
recent news articles with with the word in context.

Bias in the “added attractions” where m/w showed its commitment to the
language. Other words appearing in 1646 were (~ some ..) additionally,
jejune non-existent, testosterone, ...

Dictionary.com’s bait was aquifer quiz on slang: an 11 question multiple choice
quiz where it took me to the fifth question to realize the correct
response was always their first choice.  The best I can offer them is
that their randomizes code wasn’t working in either the browser or on
their server.

Also, their contemporary quotes where from the “”daily Beast”, where
the M/W were from The NY Times.  .

Dictionary.com has a different audience, no doubt.  Lets give them credit for
encouraging the early learners an opportunity to explore this language
we live in.

-------

writers note: This was composed on an iPad mini in the Notes section
of a Fastmail client using a Bluetooth keyboard resting on a clipboard
on my knees.

It’s now an hour later then when i began.  This choice of writing was
dictated by not wanting to sit down ant a computer, use the more
accessible tools , looking for the way to get the most words down in
the least amount of time.  The research was approximately half the
hour.

The [[token function]] is a function returning a key-board entered token. 

Here it is:

```
token () 
{ 
    : lesson: how do i turn off echo in a terminal?;
    : https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5633472/how-do-i-turn-off-echo-in-a-terminal;
    while true; do
        printf "token: " > /dev/tty;
        read -s token < /dev/tty;
        [[ ${#token} -gt 5 ]] && { 
            echo $token;
            return
        };
        echo token is NOT gt 5 > /dev/tty;
    done
}
```

The purpose of course, is to collect a "token", e.g. password, to supply to a crypt program reading an encrypted password file, whose name is undisclosed and on a private un-networked file.

The last lesson was solved at stack-overflow.  I'd been reading in shell scripts for a while, mostly as a pause in a shell function  to display traces, values etc.

I thought it useful to require the token to be six or more characters, in this age of snooping.   It's working fine.   I'll document the library when I can change passwords on the fly and save the encrypted file safely. 







Professor Wang,


    Congratulations on your appointment as Department Head.  


    I fondly remember my days in MechE at MIT: my thesis of "The Aerodynamics of the Golf Ball" under Bill Heiser, and especially Ascher Shapiro attending my presentation. 

   My contributions to the 'historical record':  "The Software Assembly Line" IEEE '83, with Bill Anderson, reflects a MechE perspective on a job not usually associated with necessary rigor.   This past year, I've contributed data analysis to Harry Moser's (MIT '66, Course 2) Reshoring Initiative.  Possibly my most significant contribution is US Patent #5559520:  Wireless Information System for Acquiring Location Related Information, while at AT&T Bell Labs, 9/24/1996.

   Challenged by your desire to develop mechanisms and initiatives that support the collaborations needed to increase our global impact, I encourage you to frame the initiatives in ways to support a National Industrial Policy. I believe this will become a necessary feature of an age greatly reshaping the nature of work.

[[TW Troubles]]


I"m starting this page [[today|1st June 2018]], when I first became aware of the problem.

While composing in TW on my computer, a file may be linked using the `file://` protocol favorably using the relative path.  When copied (via ftp) to the server, these links don't work.   This tends to discourage using TW to link to other pages, not in the same Wiki.

I'll keep my eye on this.

I discovered [[Typora|https://typora.io/]] in [[January 2019]], trying to ease the Markdown formatting of few writing threads.   I'll save that exposition for later.

So now, rather than have a function to produce the HTML from a markdown (suffix .md) file,  I keep an open copy of Typora on the desktop and point it at the file.   It's also a good idea to set the default application of .md files to Typora.






!!!! [[US Covid Origins]]

While covid is first mentioned in [[January 2020]], the statistical data becomes available in [[March 2020]] in an article titled [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_United_States]]






```
value_lock ()
{
    set $(myname 2) $*
    report_notfunction $1 && return 1;
    [[ -f .$1 ]] || {
        : default value is empty
        echo > .$1;
        touch .value_lock;
        ( cat .value_lock;
        echo $1 ) | sort -u > .value_tmp && mv .value_{tmp,lock}
    };
    [[ $# -gt 1 ]] && {
        : remaining arguments are stored, allowing phrase
        echo ${*:2} > .$1
    };
    cat .$1
}
```
As a trade-off, to eliminate local variables, set the name of the calling function: `myname 2` as the first argument, followed by any others.  Any arguments, possibly a phrase is stored in the .{name} file.

usage looks like:

```
$ aa () { value_lock $*; }
$ aa this 
$ aa              # returns "this", default is function name
$ unset aa; aa    # clears any value
$ aa this is aa   # stores a new value, phrase
```

> DRY: ''D''on't ''R''epeat ''Y''ourself
A: Here is [[what DRY is not about|https://hackernoon.com/this-is-not-the-dry-you-are-looking-for-a316ed3f445f]].  backtrack to [[sayings]].  The paper caught my attention because of these remarks:

> Do not replicate a pattern. If you find a duplicated one, refactor.  Violations of this rule will immediately be pointed out by other developers as an infringement of one of the most fundamental practices of software development.  Well, let me be honest on this one. ''This approach is completely wrong.''

and:

> Shared kernels or libraries, evergrowing Util namespaces (we all have one), inheritance trees. All in the name of an irrational need to avoid writing two similar pieces of code.

In my case, it's my UtilLib in my [[bash SHELF|https://github.com/applemcg/bash]].  A quick inspection of the library suggests a few directions:

* a command line library, functions behaving like scripts,
* classes around other commands, like awk.
* others to return to their underlying commands, i.e. "duplicate code".   a good example of this is functions behaving like an //alias//, e.g:

   ```
    $ ff () { declare -f ${*:-ff}; }
```

    where aliases may be used on the command line, but not in a function or script.

See DossysReply to my question, basically restated, "I'm sure I need this, why?"







{{LastTwoWeeks}}






This little collection flies under the title: [[Where's the Input|WherestheInput]].  The main function: stdinFileArgs
 retrieves input from:

* stdin - no arguments
* File - or file arguments
* Args - if not file argument


```
stdinFileArgs () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-08-15;
    case $# in 
        0)
            report_notpipe && return 1;
            cat -
        ;;
        *)
            [[ -f $1 ]] && { 
                cat $*
            } || echo $*
        ;;
    esac
}
report_notpipe () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-02-16;
    [[ -p /dev/stdin ]] && return 1;
    report_usage is NOT reading a pipe
}
report_usage () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-02-16;
    : date: 2018-03-30;
    echo USAGE $(myname 3): $* 1>&2
}
myname () 
{ 
    : ~ [n];
    : returns name of caller OR callers caller ...;
    : date: 2018-02-16;
    echo ${FUNCNAME[${1:-1}]}
}
rotNN () 
{ 
    : date: 2018-08-15;
    stdinFileArgs $* | tr 0-9 9876543210
}
```

The latter function shows a traditional usage:   here is how you might use it:

```
test_rotNN () 
{ 
    echo 6/6/70 | rotNN;
    rotNN 6 6 70;
    ls a* > a.txt;
    rotNN a.txt
}
$ test_rotNN | grep 9
3/3/29
3 3 29
79879293
$
```
The report_not, report_usage, and myname functions challenge the [[DRY argument|WhatIsDry]].   The report_ family is so ubiquitous in my function usage, that I show these few which are used here.

In order to turn the reporting functions into assertions, the usage would look like:


```
assert_something ... || return N
```


which would require logic inversion in report_not functions.   


```
report_notsomething && return NN
```


Maybe test a few to see how it feels






At last, after a few aborted attempts, I've settled on a [[wordcount]] tool family.  

!! The requirements:

* from my Dropbox folder
* find all the `useful` files
* from just the `text source` files
* using the ''wc'' command, record the current number of lines, words, and characters for each file

Here, a //useful// file is one which:

* doesn't have a space in its name, 
* nor is a hidden file, 
* nor in a hidden directory,
* and is not an editor backup copy, 
* nor in a visible backup directory

And //text source// is a file whose suffix implies

* an emacs OrgMode file,
* a Markdown source file
* a text file (//src// or //txt //suffix)
* and explicitly is this html file: MyIdeaWarehouse

!! Usage

Any time, the `wordcount_tally` function tabulates the current data in an [[RDB|rdb]] table.   A function converts the insert_time to an insert_date, so history may be displayed by date. 

The wc command produces a total value for the character, word, and line columns.   The last tally of the day is used to report the `wordcount_changes`.  This function returns the number of words changed (i.e. added) and a (default 5 day) moving average of the changes.

Here is the up-to-date table:


```
i_date	changes	mvag
------	-------	----
190610	312	 312.0
190611	1974	 644.4
190612	662	 647.9
190614	557	 629.7
190615	555	 614.8
190616	1189	 729.6
190617	643	 712.3
190618	532	 676.2
190619	782	 697.4
```
